
OBJECTIVE
•	To generate a continuous Sawtooth (Ramp) Wave at Port 2 (P2) of an 8051 microcontroller. 

ALGORITHM

1.	Initialize: Load the Accumulator (A) with the starting value 00H.
2.	Output: Send the current value of the Accumulator to Port 2.
3.	Increment: Increase the value of the Accumulator by 1 (INC A).
4.	Check Boundary: Compare the value of A with FFH.
  o	If A is not FFH, jump back to the Output step.
  o	If A reaches FFH, let it overflow or manually reset it to 00H.
5.	Repeat: Continue the loop infinitely to maintain a periodic ramp signal.

CODE

START: 
    MOV A, #00H  ; Initialize A to 0

LOOP:  
    MOV P2, A    ; Output the digital value to Port 2
    INC A        ; Increment the value to create the ramp
    JNZ LOOP     ; Jump to LOOP if A is not zero (loops 00H to FFH)
    
    SJMP START   ; Once A overflows to 00H, restart the ramp
    END

PROCEDURE

1. Power ON the 8051 Trainer Kit.
2. Enter the program by selecting the A (Address) option and specifying the starting address 4100.
3. Enter the assembly instructions starting from address 4100.
4. Execute the program using the GO command followed by the starting address 4100.
5. Connect the Port 2 pins to a DAC (Digital-to-Analog Converter) and observe the output on an Oscilloscope (CRO) to verify the sawtooth waveform.

EXPECTED OUTPUT

The output will be a Ramp Waveform. Unlike the triangular wave which has a rising and falling slope, the sawtooth wave rises linearly and then drops instantly back to the baseline.
•	Rise Time: Determined by the execution speed of the INC and MOV instructions.
•	Fall Time: Instantaneous (vertical drop) when the register resets from FFH to 00H.
•	Peak Amplitude: +5V (representing FFH).
•	Base Amplitude: 0V (representing 00H).




